title: In Greenland, Trump's approach turns the population against the US
subhed: Shocked by the US president's threats to seize the Inuit island, residents of Greenland are voicing their anger in Nuuk, the capital, on Saturday. In just a few weeks, the appeal once held by the American dream has vanished.

Trump taps former British prime minister Tony Blair, US military head for Gaza
subhed: A controversial figure in the Middle East because of his role in the 2003 invasion of Iraq, Blair spent years focused on the Israeli-Palestinian issue as representative of the 'Middle East Quartet' – the United Nations, European Union, United States and Russia – after leaving Downing Street in 2007.

title: 'That 'Stranger Things' brings Prince or David Bowie back to life is both wonderful and dreadful'
subhed: In the final episode of the hit Netflix series, 15- to 25-year-olds discovered 'Purple Rain' and 'Heroes,' whose streams have soared across music platforms. Unfortunately, the younger generation has limited itself to these snippets, showing little interest in the artists or their discographies, writes Michel Guerrin, editor-in-chief of Le Monde, in his column.

title: Is it ever a good idea to... wear white in winter?
subhed: In fashion, as in life, it is important to know the lines you should not cross. Or else, to do so deliberately.

title: Mercosur-EU: What the trade deal contains for the agriculture, minerals and industrial sectors
subhed: Despite the controversy, the free trade agreement between the EU and four countries in the Mercosur trade bloc will have a limited economic impact. Its implementation is set to be very gradual, while containing several safeguards.

title: Long before coveting Greenland, the US expanded by opening its checkbook
subhed: From the early 19th century on, the United States expanded by acquiring territory through purchase or force. By expressing interest in Greenland, Donald Trump has revived that tradition.
